      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implement error handling for HTTP status codes (e.g., 429 for rate limits). Use connection pooling and timeouts (e.g., 30 seconds) to manage network issues. For batch processing, queue requests asynchronously to avoid throttling."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Performance Tuning and Scalability"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimize performance by leveraging the multi-model API's ability to cache voice models locally after first use. Reduce latency by pre-warming the API with dummy requests during off-peak hours. Scale horizontally by distributing requests across multiple API keys or endpoints, and monitor throughput using metrics like requests per second and audio generation time. Consider compressing audio outputs (e.g., using Opus codec) to minimize bandwidth usage in high-volume scenarios."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Error Handling and Logging"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common errors include 400 (bad request) for malformed JSON, 401 (unauthorized) for invalid keys, and 500 (server error) for model failures. Implement exponential backoff for retries on 5xx errors, with a maximum of 3 attempts. Log all API interactions with timestamps, request IDs, and response codes for auditing. Use structured logging (e.g., JSON format) to integrate with monitoring tools like Prometheus or ELK stack, ensuring quick diagnosis of issues in production."
          }
        ]
      }
